    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2962037028" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2962037028" />
    <a title="Linda C." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/142073-linda-c"><img alt="Linda C." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1182361969p2/142073.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2962037028?book_show_action=true">Sep 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Linda C." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Linda C." href="/user/show/142073-linda-c">Linda C.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780674035355" href="/book/show/6557372-orlando-furioso">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2962037028" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7114430963889599580">My biggest complaint about Slavitt&apos;s version deals with editorial decisions made by his publisher, Belknap Press. He submitted a complete translation, but the editors released an abridged version in what I consider to be a bizarre manner. At first there were stanzas that did not appear, then entire cantos were deleted. A second volume of his translation, &quot;Lacunae: the missing cantos and stanzas of Ariosto’s Orlando furioso,&quot; was published a year later by a different publisher, (Outpost19) and re</span>
  <span id="freeText7114430963889599580" style="display:none">My biggest complaint about Slavitt's version deals with editorial decisions made by his publisher, Belknap Press. He submitted a complete translation, but the editors released an abridged version in what I consider to be a bizarre manner. At first there were stanzas that did not appear, then entire cantos were deleted. A second volume of his translation, "Lacunae: the missing cantos and stanzas of Ariosto’s Orlando furioso," was published a year later by a different publisher, (Outpost19) and reveals the redacted content from the first volume. So for scholars or devotees of the poem to read Slavitt’s translation in its entirety, you would need two books open and go back and forth between each one. <br /><br />There is not even an unabridged ebook version available that would allow a reader to read from start to finish. I am surprised the editors at Belknap Press did not try to sell an unabridged ebook version, as there is no worry about page count being a factor to determine the physical cost of an item. I would think Slavitt’s fans would prefer to read his work from start to finish in one place rather than have to go back and forth between two abridged versions. <br /><br />Beyond my misgivings about the editorial decisions made about what to include and what to redact, I have a fundamental difficulty with Slavitt’s translation. In his preface he references other translations and gives the opinion that Barbara Reynolds’ version was not “funny enough, or sprightly enough.” Slavitt expressed a desire to make the story livelier than what Reynolds had done. However, I found his translation to be problematic because I regarded his attempts to be entertaining as going overboard. I winced at historical anachronisms and did not get very far before I set his version aside. <br /><br />I will give you two examples of where I found myself pulled out of the story by his modernisms.<br /><br />Canto 2, verse 10:<br /><br />Rinaldo raises up Fusberta, which,<br />believe it or not, is the name of his broadsword. <br />Sacripant holds out his shield, a rich<br />construction of bone and steel. But it’s cardboard<br />when the sword slices right through it. (Son of a bitch!)<br />He sits on the ground and asks for misericord.<br />Angelica, seeing what has happened, is not<br />at all pleased. You do remember the plot?<br /><br /><br />Cardboard. Slavitt used the word cardboard so that it would rhyme with broadsword. Cardboard was not around in the ninth century. I felt whipsawed between medieval and modern periods. Slavitt also included the modern phrase “son of a bitch” that was definitely not part of Ariosto’s text. <br /><br />Compare to Barbara Reynold’s version (Penguin Classics):<br /><br />Canto 2, verse 10:<br /><br />Behold, with sword upraised, Rinaldo run<br />And all his might against the pagan fling,<br />Who looks to safety from his shield of bone;<br />Fine steel, well-tempered, is its armouring.<br />The blade, Fusberta, severs it in one<br />Resounding blow, making the forest ring.<br />Like ice, both steel and bone the impact cracks.<br />Nerveless, the pagan’s arms all feeling lacks.<br /><br />Such a difference. This one verse demonstrates Reynolds’s skill in making a scene come alive with sound and substance. I feel Slavitt’s version lacks respect for the source material in an attempt to show how he thinks Ariosto should have written it. His version is more of an adaptation than it is a translation.<br /><br />Here is a second example of me being pulled out of the story by Slavitt. (This is only the first half of an eight line verse.) <br /><br />Canto 6, verse 54: <br /><br />You think it’s easy? No it’s very hard<br />to say nice things to a tree – about how its bark<br />is worse than its bite? You can’t even send a card<br />unless it has that recycled paper mark.<br /><br />That passage made me stop reading. The mention of cards and recycled paper marks yanked me back to the 21st century. Ninth century correspondence was done on parchment scrolls. I don’t even feel obligated to share what Barbara Reynolds wrote. Slavitt is just awful when it comes to striving for a tonal historical continuity. <br /><br />At that point, I began surveying the volume as a whole and discovered entire cantos devoted to the love story of Bradamante and Ruggiero were missing. My favorite storyline in the poem had been minimized by the editors rendering the volume useless as source material for my writing project of adapting this poem into novels for modern day readers. Besides that, his translation was too loosey-goosey for me. I realized I did not need Slavitt’s version on my bookshelf and so I gave my copy away to a friend. <br /><br />I have no interest in buying the “missing cantos” to see how Slavitt treated the storyline of Bradamante and Ruggiero. It is likely there would be more teeth grinding moments for me similar to the “cardboard” and “recycled paper mark” ones.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7114430963889599580" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


